AGI -&nbsp;It was the &nbsp;<b>17 April of 1944</b>&nbsp; when, with the <b> operation by the code name "Balena"</b>, the Quadraro was surrounded by the German troops and systematically razed with the intent to break the resistance of a neighborhood that the Nazis had nicknamed "Nido of wasps. &nbsp;<b> Several hundred people, all men, deported to Germany following rakeling; many of them did not return. This year on the occasion of the anniversaries, the Municipality of Rome has decided the initiation of a road to the deported of the Quadraro and a monument.&nbsp;
During the ceremony, mayor Gualtieri announced the creation by Roma Capitale of a special e-mail address to which, starting today, they will be able to write the relatives of the razed people not yet tracked, as well as anyone else can help renounce the threads of the stories of those 80 years ago he was involved in the ferocious Nazi action.&nbsp; This is the e-mail address: rastrellamentodelquadraro@comune.roma.it>
&nbsp;
“The trimming of the Quadraro is one of the darkest episodes of Rome occupied by the Nazis. A crime carried out with cynical determination and ferocity to prove that they could also enter the neighborhood where the bravest fighters lived." So the Mayor of Rome, Roberto Gualtieri.
“A dowel of the battle between tyranny and freedom > which crossed the city in those years and which had other tragic moments, including the rake of the Ghetto and the massacre of the Ardeatine Fosse. A tragedy that has emptied a whole neighborhood, whose size is still subject to research, towards which there has been a lack of attention from the public memory; for this we feel that we have done today an act of justice, with the initiation of a road to the 'Deports of the Quadraro' and with the collaboration that like Rome Capital we want to offer to the research and reconstruction of the stories of all deported people, to return them finally dignity and gratitude and to continue without pause to cultivate memory".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2>Morassut (Pd), the darkest page of the Nazi occupation
&nbsp; "The trimming of the Quadraro, a symbol of the Resistance district, is one of the darkest and most painful pages of the Nazi occupation of Rome". So the Democratic Congressman, a member of the Bureau of the Chamber's PD group, Roberto Morassut, intervened today in Montecitorio to recall the drama of those days. "This day - added Morassut - must be celebrated in the highest institutional offices because &nbsp; represents a deep wound for our country, not only for Rome. The Nazis backed by the Republichina police have committed hefty crimes and wounds are still open. We must remember and hand over the memory, especially to the new generations, because &nbsp; stragi, eccidi, the ethnic cleansing we have lived in the past are a warning for the future", concluded Morassut.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2> Perissa (FdI), of primary importance
"Today the 80th anniversary of the Quadraro's Raketing, during which the Nazi-fascist troops rallied about 2000 people in the neighborhood site in the southern quadrant of the capital." is what it declares in a note Marco Perissa, Member and Roman coordinator of Brothers of Italy. "Over a thousand of them were deported and forced to work in concentration camps in Germany. It is of primary importance that this city remembers those who have suffered these shameful acts because through memory young generations will be able to refuse the language of violence and prevarication," he concludes.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The rake has been remembered in these days with several initiatives that have seen the protagonist also the municipality of Rome
&nbsp;

